<p>Building a columns layout with this framework is very simple:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Add a <code>.columns</code> container</li>
  <li>Add as many <code>.column</code> elements as you want</li>
</ol>

<p class="notification"><strong>Note:</strong> The <code>.column</code> class may be omitted, as every direct child will implicitly be an column element. ✨</p>

<p>Each column will have an equal width, no matter the number of columns.</p>

<p>Columns will have no gap by default but can be chosen. See the <a href="#gap">Gap</a> section for available configurations. For the sake of demo columns on this page, a default gap is set (<code>gap-s</code>).</p>

{% snippet %}
<div class="columns">
  <div class="column">
    <div>First</div>
  </div>
  <div class="column">
    <div>Second</div>
  </div>
  <div class="column">
    <div>Third</div>
  </div>
  <div class="column">
    <div>Fourth</div>
  </div>
</div>
{% endsnippet %}

<h2>Sizes</h2>

<p>If you want to change the size of a single column, you can use one of the following classes:</p>
<ul>
  <li><code>.span-full</code></li>
  <li><code>.span-half</code></li>
  <li><code>.span-twothirds</code></li>
  <li><code>.span-onethird</code></li>
  <li><code>.span-onequarter</code></li>
  <li><code>.span-onefifth</code></li>
</ul>

<p>The other columns will fill up the remaining space automatically.</p>

{% snippet %}
<div class="columns">
  <div class="column span-twothirds">
    <code>.span-twothirds</code>
  </div>
  <div class="column">
    <div>Auto</div>
  </div>
  <div class="column">
    <div>Auto</div>
  </div>
</div>
{% endsnippet %}

