<h2>Narrow column</h2>

<p>If you want a column to only take the <strong>space it needs</strong>, use the <code>.span-narrow</code> modifier. The other column(s) will fill up the remaining space.</p>

{% snippet %}
<div class="columns">
  <div class="column span-narrow">
    <div class="box" style="width: 200px;">
      <p class="heading-4">Narrow column</p>
      <p>This column is 200px wide.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="column">
    <div class="box">
      <p class="heading-4">Flexible column</p>
      <p>This column will take up the remaining space available.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
{% endsnippet %}

<p>As for the size modifiers, you can have narrow columns for different breakpoints:</p>
<ul>
  <li><code>.span-narrow@sm</code></li>
  <li><code>.span-narrow@md</code></li>
  <li><code>.span-narrow@lg</code></li>
</ul>

<h2>Responsiveness</h2>

<p>By default, columns don't stack e.g. on mobile automatically. They are always activated. If you want columns behave differently – say on mobile – just add a breakpoint modifier on the corresopnding column element.</p>

<p>You can define a column size for each breakpoint size: <strong>sm</strong>, <strong>md</strong>, <code>lg</code>. An example column with the modifiers <code>.span-12</code>, <code>.span-auto@sm</code> and <code>.span-narrow@lg</code> will:</p>
<ul>
  <li>span the whole viewport</li>
  <li>from the small breakpoint (640px) <strong>onwards</strong> span equally wide in relation to the other column's</li>
  <li>from the large breakpoint (1024px) <strong>onwards</strong> take only the space it needs</li>
</ul>

{% snippet %}
<div class="columns">
  <div class="column span-12 span-auto@sm span-narrow@lg">
    <code>.span-12<br>
    .span-auto@sm<br>
    .span-narrow@lg</code>
  </div>
  <div class="column">
    <div>Remaining Space</div>
  </div>
</div>
{% endsnippet %}

<p>As for the size modifiers, you can have narrow columns for different breakpoints:</p>
<ul>
  <li><code>.span-narrow@sm</code></li>
  <li><code>.span-narrow@md</code></li>
  <li><code>.span-narrow@lg</code></li>
</ul>

<h2>Gaps</h2>

<p>Each column has a gap equal to the custom property <code>--column-gap</code>, which has a default value of <code>0</code>.</p>

<p>You can specify a custom column gap by setting the <code>--column-gap</code> custom property on the <code>.columns</code> container.

{% snippet %}
<div class="columns" style="--column-gap: var(--space-l);">
  <div class="column">
    <div>Auto</div>
  </div>
  <div class="column">
    <div>Auto</div>
  </div>
  <div class="column">
    <div>Auto</div>
  </div>
</div>
{% endsnippet %}
